30
00:02:26,260 --> 00:02:33,250
Another big scope concept is scope creep,
and at times it's Pat's biggest fear.

31
00:02:33,250 --> 00:02:38,870
Scope creep is when scope is added to the
deliverables, plans or promise to stakeholders

32
00:02:38,870 --> 00:02:44,870
without truly planning the impacts on resources,
costs and schedule.

33
00:02:44,870 --> 00:02:50,840
This can happen if the project approaches
scope creep as being a bad thing without prioritizing

34
00:02:50,840 --> 00:02:54,900
what can be removed to accommodate the scope
change.

35
00:02:54,900 --> 00:03:01,510
Scope creep can be Pat's nightmare and create
a lot of stress if not managed.

36
00:03:01,510 --> 00:03:08,840
Bailey, the BA can easily and unknowingly
create scope creep in conversations with stakeholders.

37
00:03:08,840 --> 00:03:14,170
Being aware of this dynamic and working with
Pat in these situations is critical.

38
00:03:14,170 --> 00:03:20,110
Scope creep can also be a positive thing if
managed well between Pat and Bailey.

39
00:03:20,110 --> 00:03:25,680
If a stakeholder discussion yields new features
that were not previously planned, there needs

40
00:03:25,680 --> 00:03:32,180
to be an understanding of the value of the
feature in question and the priority of it.

41
00:03:32,180 --> 00:03:37,550
If it truly will make or break the value delivered
and it's a top priority, then it should be

42
00:03:37,550 --> 00:03:43,480
